木棍摆在小溪上架起一座桥。他一个人做了所有事情。马修的妈妈劳拉·兰德尔希望她的儿子获得技能和信心，仅仅靠独自一人做事。但终有一天，她不能仅靠命令她七岁的儿子拿着园艺工具在外面玩儿。他们用兰德尔所说的独立实验逐渐地解决了这个问题。“只有那些时刻，越来越长的时刻，他可以选择成为他们自己。兰德尔解释说，兰德尔知道这不是今天标准的育儿方式。当孩子们一个人骑着自行车直到街灯亮起的日子已经一去不复返了。兰德尔见过一些人认为她是一个不称职的父母。有一次，当她跑进了一家商店，一个下班的警官在马修独自一人坐在车上几分钟的时候开始冲她大喊大叫。\\n兰德尔知道，几个州的父母已经因让孩子自己走着去公园、甚至允许他们自己去上学而被逮捕。所以她对这个人的可能会做的事情有点担心。不管怎样，他们说出来了，那人走了，兰德尔对守卫自己的育儿方式感到很有信心。部分是因为她与自由放养儿童小组有过联系。这一组推动了儿童独立，给家庭带来了信息，那就是他们需要抵制过度保护的文化。\",\"questionOpt\":\"522;523;524;525;526;527;528;529;530;531;532;533;534;535;536;537;538;539;540;541\",\"questionBody\":\"（201811）Walking through the woods alone can be a frightening prospect for a kid, but not for 7-year-old Matthew of Portland, Oregon. He doesn’t have a backyard to 1_____in, so the woods behind his house serve the same 2_____. He spends hours out there: swinging on a swing, 3_____ across the valley to a friend’s house, and 4_____ garden knives to cut a path. He lays 5_____ sticks to form a bridge across the small stream. And he does all of this alone.\\nMatthew’s mom, Laura Randall, wants her son to gain skills and confidence that only 6_____with doing things alone. But she didn’t just 7_____ her 7-year-old outside the door with garden tools one day. They worked up to it gradually with what Randall calls “experiments in independence.”\\n“Just those moments, increasingly longer moments, where he can choose to be 8 _____his own,” Randall explains. Randall knows this isn’t the 9_____ for today’s parenting style. Gone are the days 10______kids ride their bikes alone until the streetlights come on.\\nRandall has met people who think she’s a 11______ parent. Once, an off-duty police officer started yelling at her when she left Matthew alone in the car 12_____ a few minutes while she ran into a shop.\\nRandall knows that parents in several states have been arrested for 13____ their kids walk to the park alone, or even 14_____ them to walk to school. And so she was a bit 15_____ about what this man might do.\\nAnyway, they talked it out, and the man walked 16______. Randall felt confident about 17___ her parenting, partly 18______ she had connected with a group 19___ Free Range Kids. This group 20______ childhood independence, and gives families the information they need to push back against a culture of overprotection.<p><br></p>\"},{\"questionResolve\":\"一、文章大意\\n及结构分析本文从想学习艺术的学生杰登·海尔斯顿入手，道出了美国政府对国家艺术基金的投入政策的变化以及各方的意见。\\n三、文章长难句分析\\nHSA  is  one  of  many  nonprofit  groups  that  bridgesthis  gap  by  offering affordable arts classes.\\n句子结构分析：“bridges this gap by offering affordable arts classes.”是一个定语从句修饰限定先行词“one of many nonprofit groups”。\\n四、核心词汇\\ndisappointed感到失望的nonprofit   非盈利的grant   补助金，拨款fund由......资助\\n五、文章翻译\\n杰登·海尔斯顿非常失望。他最想学的是唱歌。他在纽约北部扬克斯学校没有提供他需要的音乐指导。所以他请求父母为他报名课后辅导。杰登的母亲想帮助她的儿子追随他的热情。（79）但私人课程太贵了。当时6岁的杰登知道该怎么做。他拿出了他的iPad。然后他开始寻找课后艺术项目。他很快就浏览了纽约哈莱姆艺术学院的网站，在那里他可以上声乐和舞蹈课。离扬克斯有点远。但他说服父母带他去参观。那是三年前的事了。现在，杰登是HSA最活跃的学生之一。他几乎每天放学后都上唱歌、跳舞或戏剧课。（80）去年，他演出了七部作品。像杰登一样，美国许多社区的学生在学校接触艺术乐器的机会有限。HSA是众多非营利组织之一，它通过提供可负担的艺术课程来缩小这个差距。像HSA这样的组织是靠捐赠和国家补助金提供资金。许多人还由联邦政府的国家艺术的基金提供资金。国家艺术基金成立于1965年，其目标是促进所有美国人接触艺术。然而，有些人认为，提供艺术基金不是联邦政府的责任。唐纳德·特朗普（Donald Trump）总统2019年的提案呼吁国会减少了资金，以及最终取消了该机构。特朗普政府认为，私人和其他公共资源已经为艺术提供了资金。国会还没有做出决定。艺术教育的支持者说，削减国家艺术基金是一个坏主意。它可能会使许多孩子无法参加艺术活动。这是因为40%的机构补助金是用于高贫困地区。\",\"questionOpt\":\"516;517;518;519;520\",\"questionBody\":\"（201811）Passage3\\nQuestion 1 to 5 are based on the following passage:\\nJayden Hairston was very disappointed. More than anything in the world, he wanted to learn how to sing. His school in Yonkers-just north of New York City-didn’t offer the music instruction he needed. So he begged his parents to sign him up for after-school lessons.\\nJayden’s mother wanted to help her son follow his passion. (79) But private lessons were too expensive. Jayden, then 6 years old, knew exactly what to do. He took out his iPad. Then he began researching after-school arts programs. He soon came across the website for Harlem School of the Arts (HSA), in New York City. There, he could take voice and dance lessons. It was a bit far from Yonkers. But he convinced his parents to take him for a visit.\\nThat was three years ago. Now Jayden is one of HAS’s most active students. He takes singing, dancing, or theater lessons almost every day after school. (80) Last year, he performed in seven productions.\\nLike Jayden, students in many communities across the United States have limited access(使用的机会或权利) to arts instruction in schools. HSA is one of many nonprofit groups that bridges this gap by offering affordable arts classes. Groups like HSA are funded by donations(捐赠)and state grants. Many also receive money from the federal government’s National Endowment(基金) for the Arts (NEA).\\nThe NEA was established in 1965. Its goal is to promote access to the arts for all Americans. Some people, however, believe it’s not the responsibility of the federal government to provide arts funding. President Donald Trump’s 2019 proposal calls on Congress to reduce NEA funding and eventually eliminate the agency, The Trump administration argues that “private and other public sources” already provide funding for the arts. Congress has yet to make a decision.\\nSupporters of arts education say cutting the NEA is a bad idea. It could leave many children unable to participate in the arts. That’s because 40% of the agency’s grants go to high-poverty neighborhoods.\"},{\"questionResolve\":\"一、文章大意\\n及结构分析本文介绍了过度游戏对人们的危害，告诫我们要合理适度玩游戏\\n三、文章长难句分析\\nThey say people hooked on video games may be suffering from other mental health problems that should be treated first.\\n句子结构分析：hook on 上钩、上瘾，suffer from 患病，mental 精神上的，treat 治疗。“hookedon  video  games  may  be  suffering  from  other  mental  health problems ”是一个定语从句修饰限定“people”，\\n四、核心词汇\\nunwind展开，解开，放松critical批评的，批判的glue胶水，粘disorder紊乱control控制\\n五、文章翻译\\n玩电子游戏是一种放松或与朋友共度时光的有趣方式。在学校里，老师们使用诸如Minecraft之类的游戏来鼓励团队合作和批判性思维。（77）但对一些玩家来说。玩游戏已成为一种不健康的习惯。深夜，他们被粘在屏幕上。学习受到影响。电子游戏世界似乎比真实世界更友好。心理健康专家已经注意到了。6月，世界卫生组织（WTO）将游戏障碍列入其疾病和健康状况清单。如果一个人的游戏破坏了他或她与家人和朋友的关系，并且影响了他或她的日常活动，那么他或她可能患有这种疾病。并非所有的专家都同意过度的游戏应该被称为一种紊乱。他们说，那些沉迷于电子游戏的人可能正遭受其他心理健康问题的困扰，这些问题应该首先得到治疗。其他人认为WHO做出了正确的决定。精神病学家克利福德·苏斯曼（Clifford Sussman）治疗游戏成瘾。他说，孩子们经常感到焦虑和孤独。当父母要求他们停止玩电子游戏时，他们会生气。什么让电子游戏上瘾？游戏能刺激大脑的奖励中心。过了一会儿，大脑变得麻木。你手上没有控制器就觉得无聊。所以你就会玩得更多。健康游戏的一个关键是跟踪你玩了多长时间。苏斯曼建议每玩一小时后至少休息一小时。这给了大脑恢复的时间。认为自己可能有问题的年轻玩家应该向成年人寻求帮助。苏斯曼建议你首先回答一个简单的问题：“你是在控制游戏，还是游戏在控制你？”\",\"questionOpt\":\"510;511;512;513;514\",\"questionBody\":\"（201811）Passage 2\\nQuestion 1 to 5 are based on the following passage:\\nPlaying video games can be a fun way to unwind or spend time with friends. In schools, teachers use games like Minecraft to encourage teamwork and critical thinking.\\n(77)But for some players, gaming',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'politics',NULL,'{\"msg\":\"OK\",\"code\":200,\"dataId\":\"f6f12c45-735f-4b0c-9156-b9504953e880\",\"results\":[{\"rate\":99.91,\"suggestion\":\"block\",\"details\":[{\"contexts\":[{\"context\":\"ump）总统2019年的\"},{\"context\":\"评的，批判的\"},{\"context\":\"合作和批判性\"}],\"label\":\"politics\"},{\"contexts\":[{\"context\":\"。精神病学家克\"}],\"label\":\"abuse\"}],\"label\":\"politics\",\"scene\":\"antispam\"}],\"content\":\"\\\"译文：去年，他在七个工作室表演过。\\\",\\\"questionAnswer\\\":\\\"译文：去年，他在七个工作室表演过。\\\",\\\"questionBody\\\":\\\"（201811） Last year, he performed in seven productions.\\\"},{\\\"questionResolve\\\":\\\"译文：但是私教课太贵了。\\\",\\\"questionAnswer\\\":\\\"译文：但是私教课太贵了。\\\",\\\"questionBody\\\":\\\"（201811） But private lessons were too expensive.\\\"},{\\\"questionResolve\\\":\\\"译文：他说孩子们经常感到焦虑和孤独。考点：焦虑和孤独的翻译。\\\",\\\"questionAnswer\\\":\\\"译文：他说孩子们经常感到焦虑和孤独。\\\",\\\"questionBody\\\":\\\"（201811） He says kids often have feelings of anxiety and loneliness.\\\"},{\\\"questionResolve\\\":\\\"译文：但是对一些玩家来说，玩游戏已经成了一个不健康的习惯。\\\",\\\"questionAnswer\\\":\\\"译文：但是对一些玩家来说，玩游戏已经成了一个不健康的习惯。\\\",\\\"questionBody\\\":\\\"（201811） But for some players, gaming has become an unhealthy habit.\\\"},{\\\"questionResolve\\\":\\\"译文：然后她搬去了一个山谷，在那里她卖蔬菜和水果。考点：状语从句的翻